Summary

RQ: Can a Google-search âStrategic Default Risk Indexâ (SDRI) predict opportunistic mortgage default?

#1. Main comment â theoretical benchmark

When does a homeowner walk?

\[ \underbrace{-m_t}_{\text{payment}} \;+\;\beta\,\mathbb{E}_t[V^{\text{keep}}_{t+1}] \;<\; \underbrace{-\color{red}{\lambda_t}}_{\text{legal / credit}} \;-\;\underbrace{\color{orange}{\kappa_t}}_{\text{moving}} \;-\;\underbrace{\color{purple}{\psi_t}}_{\text{stigma}} \;+\;\beta\,\mathbb{E}_t[V^{\text{rent}}_{t+1}] \]

symbol economic content data?
\(m_t\) payment flow observed
\(\color{red}{\lambda_t}\) legal & credit penalties partly observed
\(\color{orange}{\kappa_t}\) relocation / quality gap proxied
\(\color{purple}{\psi_t}\) stigma / reputation unobserved

Q: What is the incremental value of SDRI beyond observables? Paper will benefit from clearer story

Default iff RHS â LHS > 0.
Only Pmt is directly observable; all costs need inference.
Any Google indicator must reveal or shift one of the coloured terms.

  1. Missing fundamentals â proxies for shocks to \(m_t\) or \(\mathbb{E}_t[HP]\).
  2. Legal-cost learning â searches reveal \(\color{red}{\lambda_t}\!\approx 0\) in non-recourse states.
  3. Stigma shift â buzz lowers \(\color{purple}{\psi_t}\).
  4. Neighbour contagion â coordination dynamics outside the equation.

Recourse split fits (2) but canât rule out (1), (3), (4).
Colour cue: red = pecuniary, purple = non-pecuniary.

Competing stories (I)

  • Missing fundamentals (\(m_t\), \(\mathbb{E}_t[HP]\))
    • ZIP-level HPI & borrower income unobserved â plausible
    • Paper: state HPI & unemployment controls donât kill SDRI
    • Try: add UI claims or âhousing-crashâ sentiment index
  • Legal-cost learning (\(\lambda_t\))
    • Some evidence that many HHs mis-perceive legislation â plausible
      • Aggregate shocks could = attention shocks, leading people to search
    • Paper: effect only in non-recourse states
    • Try: use variation in education, financial literacy, or legal knowledge (from surveys)
      • More data-intensive: exploit news shocks?

Competing stories (II)

  • Stigma shift (\(\psi_t\))
    • Social norms can move: media trends, generational, immigrationâ¦
    • Paper: is this main story?
    • Try: could try interact SDRI with county religiosity or other proxy for social norms
  • Neighbour contagion
    • Defaults cluster spatially; herd effect plausible
    • Paper: not tested
    • Try: add lagged neighbourhood defaults; if SDRI fades, contagion dominates
      • Harder: social networks data? (Bailey et al, etc.)

Further comments

#1. Identification strategy â IV

  • Instrument = population-weighted SDRI in other states
  • Potential issue: nationwide news shocks
    • National news shocks (e.g., CFPB rule, viral CNBC segment) that hit all states Â­simultaneously would lead to failure of exclusion restriction
  • Suggestion: Lag-structure IV â use yesterday search intensity in time-zone-shifted states Ã -la Choi-Varian

Main risk is common-shock bias toward finding significance.
Deliverable: one robustness table can neutralise this critique.

External validity â beyond conforming GSE loans

Sample: Fannie 30-yr FRMs â excludes jumbo / subprime.

  • But some evidence from 2008 shows strategic default also common in larger non-conforming loans:

    • PSID micro (Gerardi et al.Â 2018): 38 % of defaults have ability-to-pay characteristics
  • Suggestion: try find some data (CoreLogic ?) to capture jumbo & investor properties
